In Luau, which is a templating language used in Vue.js, you cannot directly use the `v-for` directive with an object property like `v.ParentName`. The `v-for` directive is designed to iterate over arrays, not object properties.

However, you can create a computed property in your Vue component to get an array from your object, and then use that array with `v-for`. Here's an example:

```javascript
new Vue({
  el: '#app',
  data: {
    items: [
      { id: 1, name: 'Parent 1' },
      { id: 2, name: 'Parent 2' },
      // ...
    ]
  },
  computed: {
    parents() {
      return this.items.map(item => item.name);
    }
  }
})
```

In the template, you can then use `v-for` with the `parents` computed property:

```html
<div id="app">
  <ul>
    <li v-for="parent in parents">{{ parent }}</li>
  </ul>
</div>
```

This will iterate over the `parents` array and display each parent name. If your data structure is different, you might need to adjust the `computed` property accordingly.

